# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: combining-character
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:combining-character/adlam-unicode-block] In June 2016, Adlam was added to the Unicode Standard with the release of version 9.0.
[src:combining-character/adlam-unicode-block] In October 2017, Google released a Noto font that supports the block, Noto Sans Adlam, although it does not handle prenasalized consonants properly.
[src:combining-character/adlam-unicode-block] On 3 October 2018, Microsoft released an updated Ebrima font to support Adlam alphabet to Windows Insiders as part of the Windows 10 version 1903 feature update, starting from build 18252.
[src:combining-character/adlam-unicode-block] Again, it does not handle prenasalized consonants properly.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] The earliest surviving Ahom inscription, the Snake Pillar inscription, dates only to the early 16th century, and scholars generally agree that the script was adapted from a proto-Shan script derived from Burmese between the late 14th and 16th centuries.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] The old Ahom language today survives in the numerous manuscripts written in this script currently in institutional and private possession.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] Dibrugarh University has a 2 Years Post Graduate Diploma course in Tai language.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] The Centre for South East Asian Studies, Gauhati University on 27 April, 2026 launched a 6-momths Certificate Course in Tai-Ahom language and Medieval Manuscriptology.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] A section of Mao-Shan people led by Prince Siu-Ka-Pha left the state of Muong-Mao-Lung in 1215 CE accompanied by three queens, two sons and a daughter.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] He was accompanied by Chiefs of five other dependant Muongs (States), their attendants and families, members of the priestly class and 9,000 soldiers.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] The Tai-Ahom language belongs to the South-West group of the Tai branch of the Tai-Kadai language family.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] In 1904 Sir George Abraham Grierson made a systematic study of the Tai-Ahom language published in The Linguistic Survey of India, Vol-II.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] Gurdon wrote about the alphabets, script, vocabulary of the Tai-Ahom language.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] It is believed that the Ahom people adopted their script from either Old Mon or Old Burmese, in Upper Myanmar.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] This is supported based on similar shapes of characters between Ahom and Old Mon and Old Burmese scripts.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] It is clear, however, that the script and language would have changed during the few hundred years it was in use.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] More recent research suggests that the development and adoption of the Tai Ahom script in Assam occurred later than traditionally assumed.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] The earliest surviving Ahom inscription, the Snake Pillar inscription, dates only to the early 16th century, suggesting that the widespread use and standardisation of the script in the Ahom kingdom took place during the late medieval period.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] The Lik Tai script featured on a 1407 Ming dynasty scroll exhibits many features of the Burmese script, including fourteen of the nineteen consonants, three medial diacritics and the high tone marker.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] According to the scholar Daniels, this shows that the Tai borrowed from the Burmese script to create their own script; the Lik Tai script was derived from the Burmese script, as it could only have been created by someone proficient in Burmese.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] Daniels also argues that, unlike previously thought, the Lik Tho Ngok script is not the origin of the other Lik Tai scripts, as the 1407 Lik Tai script shows greater similarity to the Ahom script, which has been attested earlier than the Lik Tho Ngok script.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] Other "Lik" scripts are used for the Khamti, Phake, Aiton and Tai Nuea languages, as well as for other Tai languages across Northern Myanmar and Assam, in Northeast India.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] The Lik scripts have a limited inventory of 16 to 18 consonant symbols compared to the Tai Tham script, which possibly indicates that the scripts were not developed for writing Pali.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] The various Burmese scripts that the Ahom script itself is derived from, was likely derived from the Indic, or Brahmi script, and possibly of South Indic origin.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] The Brahmic Script gradually spread to Southeast Asia (from the more western and/or northern regions of South Asia), through ports on trading routes.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] At these trading posts, ancient inscriptions have been found in Sanskrit, using scripts like the Brahmic Script, among others.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] At first, inscriptions were made in Sanskrit, Pali or various other Prakirts, but later the scripts were used to write the local Southeast Asian languages along with local varieties of the scripts being developed.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] By the 8th century, the scripts had diverged and separated into regional scripts.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] In 1920 Rai Saheb Golap Chandra Barua published the "Ahom-Assamese-English Dictionary".
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] In 1936 Ghana Kanta Barua published the Ahom Primer (with grammar).
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] In 1964, Bimala Kanta Barua and Nandanath Deodhai Phukan compiled the Ahom Lexicons(based on original Tai Manuscripts) and published by Department of Historical and Antiquarian Studies, Government of Assam.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] Samples of writing in the Ahom Script (Buranji's) remain stored in Assamese collections.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] The manuscripts were reportedly traditionally produced on paper prepared from agarwood (locally known as *sachi*) bark.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] Assamese replaced Ahom during the 17th century.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] The Ahom script is no longer used by the Ahom people to read and write in everyday life.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] However, it retains cultural significance and is used for religious ceremonies, chants and to read literature.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] Ahom's literary tradition provides a window into the past, of Ahom's culture.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] A printed form of the font was developed in 1920, to be used in the first "Ahom-Assamese-English Dictionary".
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] Like most abugidas, each letter has an inherent vowel of /a/.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] Other vowels are indicated by using diacritics, which can appear above, below, to the left, or to the right of the consonant.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] The script does not, however, indicate tones used in the language.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] The Ahom script is further complicated as it contains inconsistencies; a consonant may be written once in a word, but pronounced twice, common words may be shortened, and consecutive words with the same initial consonant may be contracted.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] The second version of this letter is *ta* and *ja* conjoined, with *ta* shortened.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] The second version is used as *va* in Sajjhaya spelling.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] This letter is not an independent vowel, but acts as a null consonant that can be combined with a vowel diacritic to write initial vowels.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] The following medial consonant diacritics are used to form consonant clusters with /l/ and /r/, such as /kl/ and /kr/.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] To write a consonant without a vowel, the virama ⟨◌𑜫⟩ is used.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] Ahom script was added to the Unicode Standard in June, 2015 with the release of version 8.0.
[src:combining-character/ahom-script] The Ahom block was expended by 16 code points with Unicode 14.0.
[src:combining-character/alveolar-consonant] The International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA) does not have separate symbols for the alveolar consonants.
[src:combining-character/alveolar-consonant] Rather, the same symbol is used for all coronal places of articulation that are not palatalized like English palato-alveolar *sh*, or retroflex.
[src:combining-character/alveolar-consonant] The bare letters [s, t, n, l], etc. cannot be assumed to specifically represent alveolars.
[src:combining-character/alveolar-consonant] The language may not make such distinctions, such that two or more coronal places of articulation are found allophonically, or the transcription may simply be too broad to distinguish dental from alveolar.
[src:combining-character/alveolar-consonant] If it is necessary to specify a consonant as alveolar, a diacritic from the Extended IPA may be used: [s͇, t͇, n͇, l͇], *etc.*, though that could also mean extra-retracted.
[src:combining-character/alveolar-consonant] The letters ⟨s, t, n, l⟩ are frequently called 'alveolar,' and the examples from the languages below are all alveolar sounds.
[src:combining-character/alveolar-consonant] Northwest Mekeo lacks coronal consonants entirely.
[src:combining-character/alveolar-consonant] A few languages on Bougainville Island and around Puget Sound, such as Makah, lack nasals and therefore [n] but have [t].
[src:combining-character/alveolar-consonant] Colloquial Samoan, however, lacks both [t] and [n] but has a lateral alveolar approximant /l/.
[src:combining-character/alveolar-consonant] (Samoan words written with *t* and *n* are pronounced with [k] and [ŋ] in colloquial speech.) In Standard Hawaiian, [t] is an allophone of /k/, but /l/ and /n/ exist.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] Individual Anatolian hieroglyphs are attested from the second and early first millennia BC across Anatolia and into modern Syria.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] A biconvex bronze personal seal was found in the Troy VIIb level (latter half of the 12th century BC) inscribed with Anatolian hieroglyphs.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] The earliest examples occur on personal seals, but these consist only of names, titles, and auspicious signs, and it is not certain that they represent language.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] Most actual texts are found as monumental inscriptions in stone, though a few documents have survived on lead strips.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] In the Neo-Hittite period, hieroglyphs may have also been used for "everyday" documents that have not survived because they were written on perishable materials.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] The first inscriptions confirmed as Anatolian hieroglyphs date to the Late Bronze Age, ca.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] After some two centuries of sparse material, the hieroglyphs resume in the Early Iron Age, ca.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] In the early 7th century BC, the Anatolian hieroglyphic script, by then aged some 700 years, was marginalized by competing alphabetic scripts and fell into oblivion.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] While almost all the preserved texts employing Anatolian hieroglyphs are written in the Luwian language, some features of the script suggest its earliest development within a bilingual Hittite-Luwian environment.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] For example, the sign which has the form of a "taking" or "grasping" hand has the value /ta/, which is precisely the Hittite word ta-/da- "to take," in contrast with the Luwian cognate of the same meaning which is la-.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] There was occasionally some use of Anatolian hieroglyphs to write foreign material like Hurrian theonyms, or glosses in Urartian (such as *á – ḫá+ra – ku* for *aqarqi* or *tu – ru – za* for *ṭerusi*, two units of measurement).
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] As in Egyptian, characters may be logographic or phonographic—that is, they may be used to represent words or sounds.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] The number of phonographic signs is limited.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] Most represent CV syllables (CV = consonant vowel), though there are a few disyllabic signs.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] A large number of these are ambiguous as to whether the vowel is *a* or *i.* Some signs are dedicated to one use or another, but many are flexible.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] Words may be written logographically, phonetically, mixed (that is, a logogram with a phonetic complement), and may be preceded by a determinative.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] Other than the fact that the phonetic glyphs form a syllabary rather than indicating only consonants, this system is analogous to the system of Egyptian hieroglyphs.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] A more elaborate monumental style is distinguished from more abstract linear or cursive forms of the script.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] In general, relief inscriptions prefer monumental forms, and incised ones prefer the linear form, but the styles are in principle interchangeable.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] Texts of several lines are usually written in boustrophedon style.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] Within a line, signs are usually written in vertical columns of two to four signs, but as in Egyptian hieroglyphs, aesthetic considerations take precedence over correct reading order.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] Many texts also employ an explicit word divider character.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] One peculiarity of the Luwian writing system is that in some texts vowel signs, usually repeating the vowel of the preceding syllable, were used to fill up sign columns, so that new words would always start at the top of the line.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] Some texts also exhibit the so-called "initial-à-final" pattern, where the word-initial *a* character is moved either to the top of the second column of signs or to the end of the word.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] Anatolian hieroglyphs first came to Western attention in the nineteenth century, when European explorers such as Johann Ludwig Burckhardt and Richard Francis Burton described pictographic inscriptions on walls in the city of Hama, Syria.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] The same characters were recorded in Boğazköy, and presumed by A.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] By 1915, with the Luwian language known from cuneiform, and a substantial quantity of Anatolian hieroglyphs transcribed and published, linguists started to make real progress in reading the script.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] In the 1930s, it was partially deciphered by Ignace Gelb, Piero Meriggi, Emil Forrer, and Bedřich Hrozný.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] Its language was confirmed as Luwian in 1973 by J.D.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] Hawkins, Anna Morpurgo Davies and Günther Neumann, who corrected some previous errors about sign values, in particular emending the reading of symbols *376 and *377 from *i, ī* to *zi, za*.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] The script consists of some 500 unique signs, some with multiple values; a given sign may function as a logogram, a determinative or a syllabogram, or a combination thereof.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] The signs are numbered according to Laroche's sign list, with a prefix of 'L.' or '*'.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] Logograms are transcribed in Latin in capital letters.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] For example, *90, an image of a foot, is transcribed as PES when used logographically, and with its phonemic value *ti* when used as a syllabogram.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] In the rare cases where the logogram cannot be transliterated into Latin, it is rendered through its approximate Hittite equivalent, recorded in Italic capitals, e.g.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] The most up-to-date sign list was compiled by Massimiliano Marazzi in 1998.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] Transliteration of logograms is conventionally the term represented in Latin, in capital letters (e.g.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] The syllabograms are transliterated, disambiguating homophonic signs analogously to cuneiform transliteration, e.g.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] *ta=ta₁*, *tá=ta₂*, and *ta₆* transliterate three distinct ways of representing phonemic /ta/.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] Some of the homophonic signs have received further attention and new phonetic interpretation in recent years, e.g. tà has been argued to stand for /da/, and á seems to have stood for /ʔa/ (distinct from /a/), representing the descendant of Proto-Indo-European */h₁/.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] Anatolian hieroglyphs were added to the Unicode Standard in June, 2015 with the release of version 8.0.
[src:combining-character/anatolian-hieroglyphs] The Unicode block for Anatolian Hieroglyphs is U+14400–U+1467F.
[src:combining-character/ancient-north-arabian] Many scholars believed that the various ANA alphabets were derived from the ASA script, mainly because the latter was employed by a major civilization and exhibited more angular features.
[src:combining-character/ancient-north-arabian] Others believed that the ANA and ASA scripts shared a common ancestor from which they both developed in parallel.
[src:combining-character/ancient-north-arabian] Indeed, it seems unlikely that the various ANA scripts descend from the monumental ASA alphabet, but that they collectively share a common ancestor to the exclusion of ASA is also something which has yet to be demonstrated.
[src:combining-character/ancient-north-arabian] The hypothesis that all ANA alphabets derive from a single ancestor gave rise to the idea that the languages which these scripts express constitute a linguistic unity, a so-called ANA *language*.
[src:combining-character/ancient-north-arabian] As a hypothetical language or group of languages, Ancient North Arabian forms one branch of the North Arabian group, the other being Proto-Arabic.
[src:combining-character/ancient-north-arabian] They are distinguished from each other by the definite article, which in Arabic is *ʾal-*, but in ANA is *h-*.
[src:combining-character/ancient-north-arabian] They belong to a different branch of the Semitic languages than the Ancient South Arabian languages.
[src:combining-character/ancient-north-arabian] The validity of this hypothesis has been called into question.
[src:combining-character/ancient-north-arabian] This is particularly the case for Taymanitic, which has been determined to be a Northwest Semitic language.
[src:combining-character/ancient-north-arabian] Safaitic and Hismaic are also now considered forms of Old Arabic due to shared features.
[src:combining-character/ancient-north-arabian] The Ancient North Arabian scripts were used both in the oases (Dadanitic, Dumaitic, Taymanitic) and by the nomads (Hismaic, Safaitic, Thamudic B, C, D, and possibly Southern Thamudic aka Thamudic F) of central and northern Arabia.
[src:combining-character/ancient-north-arabian] The most ancient examples of the script discovered date back to the 9th–8th centuries BCE and were found in Syria, Palestine, Mesopotamia, and Luristan.
[src:combining-character/ancient-north-arabian] Ancient North Arabian script has a one-to-one correspondence with the Arabic alphabet except for 𐪏‎ and 𐪊‎ which correspond to س‎.
[src:combining-character/ancient-north-arabian] Old North Arabian script was added to the Unicode Standard in June 2014 with the release of version 7.0.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] The **Ancient South Arabian script** (Old South Arabian: 𐩣𐩯𐩬𐩵, romanized: *ms3nd*; modern Arabic: الْمُسْنَد *musnad*) branched from the Proto-Sinaitic script in about the late 2nd millennium BCE, and remained in use through the late sixth century CE.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] It is an abjad, a writing system where only consonants are obligatorily written, a trait shared with its predecessor, Proto-Sinaitic, as well as some of its sibling writing systems, including Arabic and Hebrew.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] It is a predecessor of the Ge'ez script, and a sibling script of the Phoenician alphabet and, through that, the modern Latin, Cyrillic, and Greek alphabets.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] The script is really two variants: the monumental and the minuscule script, the former for inscriptions, the latter scratched with wooden sticks.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] The scripts have a common origin but evolved into separate systems.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] The earliest instances of the Ancient South Arabian (*ASA*) script are painted pottery sherds from Raybun in Hadhramaut in Yemen, which are dated to the late 2nd millennium BCE.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] It is an abjad script, meaning that only consonants are usually written in the script, with vowels inferred from context; it shares this feature both with its predecessor, the Proto-Sinaitic script, and modern Semitic languages.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] It is unclear precisely how and when the ASA script diverged from Proto-Sinaitic script, as inscriptions from its earliest days are rare.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] As with these other abjads, some vowels can be indicated if necessary, by matres lectionis.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] Its mature form was reached around 800 BCE, and it remained use in more or less the same form until the 6th century CE.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] In those centuries, it was used to write multiple languages of the Southern Arabian peninsula and the Horn of Africa, including Sabaic, Qatabanic, Hadramautic, Minaean, Hasaitic, and Geʽez.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] It was eventually displaced by the modern Arabic alphabet during the early years of the spread of Islam.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] The modern Arabic writing system is related to the ASA script, as both are children of the Proto-Sinaitic script, but modern Arabic derives from the Phoenician and Nabatean scripts rather than ASA.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] The Geʽez script is the sole extant writing system that derives from ASA.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] Unlike ASA, Geʽez is an abugida; the primary characters are pairs of consonants and vowels, with each character representing a syllable.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] Geʽez has been used to write Amharic, Tigrinya and Tigre, as well as other languages (including various Semitic, Cushitic, Omotic, and Nilo-Saharan languages).
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] ASA is also a sibling of the Phoenician – the ancestor of most of the modern European alphabets, such as Latin, Cyrillic and Greek.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] The Musnad script differs from the Arabic script, which most linguists believe developed from the Nabataean script in the fourth century AD, which in turn developed from the Aramaic script.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] The languages of the Southern Musnad script also differ greatly from the Northern Arabic language in terms of script, lexicon, grammar, styles, and perhaps sounds, and the letters of the script increase.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] The Musnad is derived from Arabic with an extra sibilant letter (some call it sāmikh) or the third sīn.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] The sign for 50 was evidently created by removing the lower triangle from the sign for 100.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] The sign for 1 doubles as a word separator.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] The other four signs double as both letters and numbers.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] Each of these four signs is the first letter of the name of the corresponding numeral.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] An additional sign (𐩿) is used to bracket numbers, setting them apart from surrounding text.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] These signs are used in an additive system similar to Roman numerals to represent any number (excluding zero).
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] Perhaps because of ambiguity, numerals, at least in monumental inscriptions, are always clarified with the numbers written out in words.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] Zabur was a writing system in ancient Yemen along with Musnad.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] The difference between the two is that Musnad documented historical events, meanwhile Zabur writings were used for religious scripts or to record daily transactions among ancient Yemenis.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] Zabur writings could be found in palimpsest form written on papyri or palm-leaf stalks.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] The South Arabian alphabet was added to the Unicode Standard in October, 2009 with the release of version 5.2.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] The Unicode block, called Old South Arabian, is U+10A60–U+10A7F.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] Note that U+10A7D OLD SOUTH ARABIAN NUMBER ONE (𐩽) represents both the numeral one and a word divider.
[src:combining-character/ancient-south-arabian-script] The inscription was published in a scientific article written by the Frenchman Christian Robin as the last official Musnad inscription.
[src:combining-character/ansel] The initial revision of ANSEL was released in 1985, and before 1993 it was registered as Registration #231 in the ISO International Register of Coded Character Sets to be Used with Escape Sequences.
[src:combining-character/ansel] The standard was reaffirmed in 2003 although it has been administratively withdrawn by ANSI effective 14 February 2013.
[src:combining-character/ansel] The requirement of hardware capable of overprinting accents made this mostly impossible from ever becoming a popular extended ASCII.
[src:combining-character/ansel] Non-ASCII characters are shown with their Unicode code point.
[src:combining-character/ansel] A combining diacritic *precedes* the spacing character on which it should be superimposed (in Unicode the combining diacritic is *after* the base character).
[src:combining-character/ansel] The GEDCOM specification for exchanging genealogical data refers to ANSEL (ANSI/NISO Z39.47-1985) as a valid text encoding for GEDCOM files and extends it with additional characters which are shown in the following table.
[src:combining-character/ansel] The Extended Latin character set from MARC 21 is synchronized with ANSEL but additionally supports the eszett (ß) character at C7 and the euro sign (€) at C8.
[src:combining-character/combining-character] In digital typography, **combining characters** are characters that are intended to modify other characters.
[src:combining-character/combining-character] The most common combining characters in the Latin script are the **combining diacritical marks** (including **combining accents**).
[src:combining-character/combining-character] Unicode also contains many precomposed characters, so that in many cases it is possible to use both combining diacritics and precomposed characters, at the user's or application's choice.
[src:combining-character/combining-character] This leads to a requirement to perform Unicode normalization before comparing two Unicode strings and to carefully design encoding converters to correctly map all of the valid ways to represent a character in Unicode to a legacy encoding to avoid data loss.
[src:combining-character/combining-character] In Unicode, the main block of combining diacritics for European languages and the International Phonetic Alphabet is U+0300–U+036F.
[src:combining-character/combining-character] Combining diacritical marks are also present in many other blocks of Unicode characters.
[src:combining-character/combining-character] In Unicode, diacritics are always added after the main character (in contrast to some older combining character sets such as ANSEL), and it is possible to add several diacritics to the same character, including stacked diacritics above and below, though some systems may not render these well.
[src:combining-character/combining-character] Combining characters are not limited to these blocks; for instance, the combining dakuten (U+3099) and combining handakuten (U+309A) are in the Hiragana block, the Devanagari block contains combining vowel signs and other marks for use with that script, and so forth.
[src:combining-character/combining-character] Combining characters are assigned the Unicode major category "M" ("Mark").
[src:combining-character/combining-character] U+034F is the "combining grapheme joiner" (CGJ) and has no visible glyph.
[src:combining-character/combining-character] Codepoints U+035C–0362 are double diacritics, diacritic signs placed across two letters.
[src:combining-character/combining-character] Codepoints U+0363–036F are medieval superscript letter diacritics, letters written directly above other letters appearing in medieval Germanic manuscripts, but in some instances in use until as late as the 19th century.
[src:combining-character/combining-character] For example, U+0364 is an *e* written above the preceding letter, to be used for (Early) New High German umlaut notation, such as *uͤ* for Modern German *ü*.
[src:combining-character/combining-character] OpenType has the *ccmp* "feature tag" to define glyphs that are compositions or decompositions involving combining characters, the *mark* tag to define the positioning of combining characters onto base glyph, and *mkmk* for the positionings of combining characters onto each other.
[src:combining-character/combining-character] Combining characters have been used to create Zalgo text, which is text that appears "corrupted" or "creepy" due to an overuse of combining characters.
[src:combining-character/combining-character] This causes the text to extend vertically, overlapping other text.
[src:combining-character/combining-character] This is mostly used in horror contexts on the Internet.
[src:combining-character/combining-character] It is typically very challenging for most software to render, so the combining marks are often reduced or completely stripped off.
